      <hedline>
        <hl1>Keep Pressing Iran Over Trial of Jews</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Jack Rosen (American Jewish Congress), commenting on July 5 editorial, says Pres Clinton and world leaders must increase pressure on Iran to reverse its wrongful convictions of 10 Jews</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>President Clinton and other world leaders have called on Iran to reverse its wrongful convictions of 10 Jews on charges of spying for Israel  (editorial, July 5), but more than words are needed. It is likely that death sentences were averted in the show trial because countries around the world made it clear that they would hold Iran accountable.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>President Clinton and other world leaders have called on Iran to reverse its wrongful convictions of 10 Jews on charges of spying for Israel  (editorial, July 5), but more than words are needed. It is likely that death sentences were averted in the show trial because countries around the world made it clear that they would hold Iran accountable.</p>
        <p>First, the olive branch extended some weeks ago by Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright must be withdrawn. It is inconceivable that economic concessions be made to Iran while these prison sentences stand.</p>
        <p>The international community must guard against the silence induced by attention fatigue. The freedom of innocent men and the security of the remaining Iranian Jewish community depend on the free world's perseverance.</p>
        <p>JACK ROSEN  Pres., American Jewish Congress  New York, July 5, 2000</p>
      </block>
